{
  "case_id": "D2N017",
  "method": "direct",
  "template": "sectioned",
  "summary_text": "Chief Complaint\nRight leg pain following a bowling injury.\n\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports right leg pain following a bowling injury. He describes hitting the bowling ball into his leg while running to the lane, resulting in a fall. He denies significant swelling but reports mild bruising to the back of his right leg. He was able to walk with some difficulty but avoided stairs. He has a history of atopic eczema treated with fluocinonide when needed and a previous surgical history of a colectomy due to diverticulitis.\n\nFindings\nPhysical examination reveals tenderness to the lateral aspect of the right upper leg. Range of motion is intact in the lower leg. X-ray demonstrates no fracture or significant swelling.\n\nAssessment\nContusion of the right upper leg.\n\nPlan\nStart mobic 15 milligrams once daily. Recommend ice packs for pain relief. Follow up in one week if symptoms do not improve. Dragon, please order the prescribed medications and procedures.",
  "reference_summary": "CC:\n\nRight leg pain.\n\nHPI:\n\nMs. Peterson is a 43-year-old female who presents today for an evaluation of right leg pain. She states she was bowling and hit her leg with the ball and fell. She developed mild bruising. She denies swelling. She has been walking very carefully. She is alternating Tylenol and ibuprofen. She has a history of atopic eczema and takes Fluocinonide topical cream for it. She has a history of colectomy following diverticulosis.\n\nEXAM\n\nExamination of the right leg shows significant tenderness to the lateral aspect of the right upper leg. No pain or tenderness with flexion or extension of the lower leg.\n\nRESULTS\n\nX-rays of the right lower extremity is normal, no fractures or dislocations.\n\nIMPRESSION\n\nRight leg contusion.\n\nPLAN\n\nAt this point, I discussed the diagnosis and treatment options with the patient. I have recommended Mobic 15 mg once a day. She will use ice for pain. She will follow up as needed.",
